    <name>
				<text>(not in quiz) 37.2.3.9 A machine that has two drive belts</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p><p>A machine has two drive belts, one on the left and one on the right. From time to time the drive belts break. When one breaks the machine is stopped and both belts are replaced.  Details of \( {@n@} \) consecutive breakages are recorded. Assume that the left and right belts are equally likely to break first. Let \( X \) be the number of times the break is on the left.</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">

<li><p>How many possible different sequences of “left” and “right” are there? [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p></li>

<li><p>How many of these sequences contain exactly {@n_lefts@} “lefts”? [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</p></li>

<li><p>Please fill the following table (<b>Note:</b> round your answer up to \(4\) decimal places).</p><table class="HELM_table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>\(j\)</th>
      <th>\(0\)</th>
      <th>\(1\)</th>
      <th>\(2\)</th>
      <th>\(3\)</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>\(\text{P} (X=j)\)</td>
      <td>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]</td>
      <td>[[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]</td>
      <td>[[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]]</td>
      <td>[[input:ans6]] [[validation:ans6]] [[feedback:prt6]]</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table></li>

</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p>SOLUTION:</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
  <li>In one breakage there are 2 possibilities: the "left" belt or the "right belt", so if there are {@n@} breakages, there are \(2^{@n@} = {@ta_1@}\) possible sequences of "left" and "right" (check the 'Multiplicative Principle').</li>
  <li><p>You should remember combinations and permutations. In particular, If you have {@n@} recorded breakages and you want to know the number of ways you can register {@n_lefts@} "left" belt broken among the {@n@} breakages, this follows a combination given by:</p><p>\( \ ^{{@n@}}\!C_{@n_lefts@} = {@ta_2@}\)</p></li>
  <li><p>\(X\) follows a binomial distribution with \(\text{P} (X=r)=\  ^n\!C_rp^r(1-p)^{n-r}\) where \(p\) is the probability of single `success' which is `left belt broken'. Thus, following this formula we have:</p><table class="HELM_table">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>\(j\)</th>
      <th>\(0\)</th>
      <th>\(1\)</th>
      <th>\(2\)</th>
      <th>\(3\)</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>\(\text{P} (X=j)\)</td>
      <td>{@ta_3@}</td>
      <td>{@ta_4@}</td>
      <td>{@ta_5@}</td>
      <td>{@ta_6@}</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table></li></ol>]]></text>
